# structured-think.gbnf — opt-in scratchpad shape for ask-cuda (Qwen3.6 dGPU).
#
# Adapted from the "Structured CoT" trick (andthattoo.dev/blog/structured_cot):
# constrain ONLY the model's <think> block to three short labelled lines, leave
# the answer/code channel unconstrained. This is *shape* control, not a hard
# token budget — `[^\n]+` is unbounded per line, matching what the blog actually
# benchmarked. If the bench shows lines blowing up, swap to `[^\n]{1,200}`.
#
# Caveats (verify on nv1, see bench-structured-cot.sh):
#   * Qwen3.6 chat templates may pre-insert `<think>\n` at the assistant turn.
#     If the grammar then fails immediately (cannot re-sample `<`), drop the
#     leading `"<think>\n"` literal from the `think` rule.
#   * Grammar matching is over the UTF-8 byte/codepoint stream, not token IDs;
#     `<think>` being a special token in the Qwen vocab does not change matching
#     but can affect which token IDs satisfy the literal. This is exactly what
#     the bench's malformed-output column is for.
#   * `answer ::= .+` is deliberately maximally permissive (`.` is GBNF
#     "any single character", incl. newline + Unicode) so code with non-ASCII
#     comments/identifiers is never blocked.

root   ::= think answer
think  ::= "<think>\n" "GOAL: " line "APPROACH: " line "EDGE: " line "</think>\n\n"
line   ::= [^\n]+ "\n"
answer ::= .+
